posts.name: Ambrish
posts.cooked:
Hello,

We have neo vortex with solo adapter and Sparkmax mounted on a shaft for our elevator. When we enable it, it doesn’t start automatically. But a little manual push is helping it.

Google Drive file.

Any thoughts/suggestion on what we may be missing ?

Thanks -Ambrish

posts.name: Joseph1825
posts.cooked: Do you have a current limit on the motor controller? It sounds like the torque of the motor is not enough to actually get your mechanism moving, but once it starts moving, the motor can keep it moving. If that’s what it is, increasing your current limit should fix it.

posts.name: Ambrish
posts.cooked: Thanks. We are using default Sparkmax settings.

posts.name: Joseph1825
posts.cooked:
Okay, I just checked it, the default sparkmax current limit should be 80 amps. That’s pretty high.

If your current is actually spiking that high and still not moving the mechanism, you would need to see why there is so much friction in your system. Or maybe see if you need to gear your motor higher. You should be able to check your output current with getOutputCurrent() in the sparkmax library.

posts.name: Domtech
posts.cooked:
ambrish3281:

When we enable it, it doesn’t start automatically. But a little manual push is helping it.

That almost always means you have a poor connection on one of the 3 phase wires.

posts.name: billbo911
posts.cooked: This same behavior also happens when one of the six sensor wires is broken.

posts.name: Ambrish
posts.cooked:
This appears to an an issue with friction. It works fine when not mounted on the shaft.

We are troubleshooting more from mechanical side at this point.

Thank you for the inputs!

posts.name: philso
posts.cooked: That is typical behavior when one of the 3 phases is not working. A 3-phase motor will sort of work when connected to only 2 of the phases. It may be as simple as one of the three output connections from the Sparkmax being bad to an internal open circuit.

posts.name: Aidan McMaster
posts.cooked: I have seen this happen when 1 of the 3 phase wires for the brushless motor is not connected

posts.name: Ambrish
posts.cooked: This is likely to be an issue with 3 phase wires. We are still seeing it even outside of shaft assembly. Thank you all for all your inputs.

posts.name: Rod
posts.cooked: Ohm your three phases…  Unfortunately the resistance is super low, so its hard to sort out open circuit vs shorted turns.

posts.name: Josh
posts.cooked: I’d also double check your spark condition. Bump starts can either be wires, or a faulty spark.
